Version: Deno 1.39.1 (Windows)

The [documentation](https://deno.land/api@v1.39.1?s=Deno.mkdir) for `mkdir` indicates that it throws an error when a directory already exists. However, when I try this locally, I cannot get it to throw an error when `{ recursive: true }` is specified. Example:

```js
Deno.mkdir(".deno-tmp");

// no error thrown
await Deno.mkdir(".deno-tmp", { recursive: true });

// also no error thrown
Deno.mkdirSync(".deno-tmp", { recursive: true });
```

The only [related test](https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/261f32ef651a6515fbac664302adcfbe34a04372/cli/tests/unit/mkdir_test.ts#L176-L178) I could find seems to indicate that an error is expected only when the path resolves to a file? [These tests](https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/261f32ef651a6515fbac664302adcfbe34a04372/cli/tests/unit/mkdir_test.ts#L138-L154) seem to indicate that it's expected that `mkdir/mkdirSync` do not throw errors at all when `{ recursive: true }` is passed.

It seems most likely that the documentation is incorrect here, or at the very least, misleading and should be updated.
